\begin{IDEA}
**Title: Geometric and Electronic Mapping of Mechanical Rigidity in TMD Polymorphs**

This study constructs a multi-variate regression model to quantify the mechanical stability of 202 TMDs, utilizing the 90 available elastic samples to isolate the structural drivers of shear modulus ($G_{vrh}$) and elastic anisotropy. By prioritizing high-fidelity geometric features—specifically `c_a_ratio`, `volume_per_atom`, and `phase`—the model captures the lattice-dependent constraints on rigidity that electronic descriptors alone fail to resolve. To bridge the gap between stable and metastable phases, the model incorporates `d_band_filling` and `en_difference` as secondary, physics-informed corrections to account for the electronic contributions to bond stiffness. We will employ an elastic-net regularization framework to mitigate the risk of overfitting inherent in the limited sample size, explicitly treating `phase` as a categorical constraint to distinguish between the distinct bonding topologies of 2H, 1T, and 1T' polymorphs. The final objective is to define a structural-mechanical descriptor map that predicts the elasticity of metastable TMDs by identifying the critical geometric thresholds where structural transitions induce mechanical softening or instability.
\end{IDEA}


