This study develops a machine learning framework to predict shear moduli ($G_{vrh}$) and universal elastic anisotropy indices for the 112 metastable TMDs currently lacking experimental or DFT-computed elastic constants. By utilizing the 90 materials with existing elastic data as a training set, the model integrates electronic descriptors—specifically `d_band_filling`, `dos_at_fermi`, and the `M_soc_proxy`—to capture the electronic origins of mechanical softening. The objective is to identify a predictive relationship between Fermi-level electronic density and structural rigidity, effectively mapping the mechanical stability landscape of metastable phases that would otherwise remain uncharacterized. This approach explicitly accounts for magnetic ground states and metal-chalcogen bond ionicity (`en_difference`) to isolate how electronic configuration governs elastic anisotropy in non-equilibrium TMD polymorphs.


